A lament on thefleeting character of life. ‘Alas‚ good friend, do what we will, old age and death corne on apace. No sacrifice ean stay the hand of the pitiless lord of death 3 rich and poor alike must corne unto his malm, and all thy efforts to avoid war, the sea, or fell disease are vain. Thou must leave all behind that thou holdest now most dear. Then thy stored wine, thy heir, worthier than thou, will waste.' In the last strophe Horace in negative fashion returns to his philosophy of life, ⁴ Seize the pleasure of the passing bour, and do not waste your time in gathering wealth you do not use yourself. To-morrow we alldie and another wastes our savings.'
